---

Scope of the Reference Implementation

This release includes:

• structural value definitions  
• value visibility rules  
• minimal executable reference (numeric resolution engine)  
• outputs and reference traces  

SVARE defines a deterministic structural model where value correctness emerges from structure:

resolve(structure) →

• RESOLVED if structure_uniquely_resolves  
• INCOMPLETE if structure is incomplete  
• CONFLICT if structure is inconsistent  

---

What This Demonstrates

• value correctness without computation  
• independence from arithmetic execution  
• independence from evaluation order  
• independence from floating-point approximation  
• structural resolution governing value visibility  
• safe handling of incomplete or conflicting structure  
• deterministic and reproducible value states  
• identical input structure produces identical value and certificate  

---

Conformance

An implementation is considered compatible if it preserves:

• structure-based correctness  
• independence from computation as a requirement  
• deterministic resolution  
• structure-driven value visibility  
• reproducibility of value and certificate under equivalent inputs  
• explicit handling of incomplete and conflicting structure  

Conformance is judged solely by observable behavior — not by internal implementation.

S1 = S2 → Value1 = Value2 → Certificate1 = Certificate2

---

Conflict Handling

In this reference implementation:

• CONFLICT is explicitly defined and demonstrated  
• INCOMPLETE corresponds to incomplete structure (no value)  
• inconsistent conditions do not produce a visible value  

Conformance requires:

• no forced value under incomplete structure  
• no arbitrary value under conflicting structure  

---

Canonical Value Identity (Forward Path)

Extended implementations may include canonical identity:

canonical(resolve(S)) → value_identity

This enables:

• equivalence across different valid structural representations  
• normalization of value truth  
• identity independent of representation  

This is not required for the reference implementation.

---

Relationship to Shunyaya Framework

SVARE is part of the broader Shunyaya framework.

It builds on:

• SLANG → correctness without execution  
• ORL → correctness without ordering  
• STIME → correctness without time  
• STINT → correctness without connectivity  
• STRAL → correctness without traversal  
• STILE → correctness without communication  
• SVARE → correctness without computation  

Each removes a dependency.  
Correctness remains preserved by structure.

